Stakeholder asset-mapping of climate technology infrastructures
                    Marta Koch 
            ORCID: orcid.org/0000-0003-0078-31241

Nature Reviews Earth & Environment

(2025)Cite this article







                        10 Accesses






                            1 Altmetric





                        Metrics details

Subjects

            Climate-change adaptationClimate-change mitigationClimate-change policyScience, technology and society

Access through your institution







                        Buy or subscribe

The Arctic region requires tailored and localized strategies for effective and equitable climate technology readiness and implementation. Stakeholder community asset-mapping workshops can be used to leverage local knowledge to map present and future technology infrastructures for climate adaptation and resilience. Such workshops can highlight the resources, vulnerabilities and connections shaping climate action technology capacity-building in this setting, including emerging digitalization and artificial intelligence (AI) solutions, and highlighting where future climate technology development opportunities lie.By weaving together these multi-level dimensions of climate technology governance and implementation in collaboration with local stakeholders, this approach provides a powerful tool for identifying both current and emerging climate action technology solutions in one of the world’s most climate-vulnerable regions. Critically, this workshop format allows for a more positive framing of stakeholder engagement for effective climate technology policy and implementation gap identification by bridging the ideal scenario with the present-day situation, rather than simply focusing on limitations.



